            "id": 1,
            "parent": 7,
            "text": "Porcine reproductive and respiratory syndrome ( PRRS ) has been one of the most economically important diseases",
            "relation": "BACKGROUND"
        },
        {
            "id": 2,
            "parent": 1,
            "text": "affecting swine industry worldwide",
            "relation": "ELABORATION"
        },
        {
            "id": 3,
            "parent": 1,
            "text": "and causes great economic losses each year . <S>",
            "relation": "JOINT"
        },
        {
            "id": 4,
            "parent": 1,
            "text": "PRRS virus ( PRRSV ) replicates mainly in porcine alveolar macrophages ( PAMs ) and dendritic cells ( DCs )",
            "relation": "ELABORATION"
        },
        {
            "id": 5,
            "parent": 4,
            "text": "and develops persistent infections , antibody - dependent enhancement ( ADE ) , interstitial pneumonia and immunosuppression . <S>",
            "relation": "JOINT"
        },
        {
            "id": 6,
            "parent": 5,
            "text": "But the molecular mechanisms of PRRSV infection still are poorly understood . <S>",
            "relation": "COMPARISON"
        },
        {
            "id": 7,
            "parent": 0,
            "text": "Here we report on the first genome - wide host transcriptional responses to classical North American type PRRSV ( N - PRRSV ) strain CH 1a infection",
            "relation": "ROOT"
        },
        {
            "id": 8,
            "parent": 7,
            "text": "using Solexa / Illumina 's digital gene expression ( DGE ) system , a tagbased high - throughput transcriptome sequencing method ,",
            "relation": "MANNER-MEANS"
        },
        {
            "id": 9,
            "parent": 7,
            "text": "and analyse systematically the relationship between pulmonary gene expression profiles after N - PRRSV infection and infection pathology . <S>",
            "relation": "JOINT"
        },
        {
            "id": 10,
            "parent": 11,
            "text": "Our results suggest",
            "relation": "ATTRIBUTION"
        },
        {
            "id": 11,
            "parent": 7,
            "text": "that N - PRRSV appeared to utilize multiple strategies for its replication and spread in infected pigs ,",
            "relation": "FINDINGS"
        },
        {
            "id": 12,
            "parent": 11,
            "text": "including subverting host innate immune response ,",
            "relation": "ELABORATION"
        },
        {
            "id": 13,
            "parent": 11,
            "text": "inducing an anti - apoptotic and anti - inflammatory state",
            "relation": "CAUSE-RESULT"
        },
        {
            "id": 14,
            "parent": 13,
            "text": "as well as developing ADE . <S>",
            "relation": "JOINT"
        },
        {
            "id": 15,
            "parent": 11,
            "text": "Upregulation expression of virus - induced pro - inflammatory cytokines , chemokines , adhesion molecules and inflammatory enzymes and inflammatory cells , antibodies , complement activation were likely to result in the development of inflammatory responses during N - PRRSV infection processes . <S>",
            "relation": "ELABORATION"
        },
        {
            "id": 16,
            "parent": 15,
            "text": "N - PRRSV - induced immunosuppression might be mediated by apoptosis of infected cells ,",
            "relation": "ELABORATION"
        },
        {
            "id": 17,
            "parent": 16,
            "text": "which caused depletion of immune cells",
            "relation": "CAUSE-RESULT"
        },
        {
            "id": 18,
            "parent": 17,
            "text": "and induced an anti - inflammatory cytokine response",
            "relation": "JOINT"
        },
        {
            "id": 19,
            "parent": 18,
            "text": "in which they were unable to eradicate the primary infection . <S>",
            "relation": "ELABORATION"
        },
        {
            "id": 20,
            "parent": 7,
            "text": "Our systems analysis will benefit for better understanding the molecular pathogenesis of N - PRRSV infection , developing novel antiviral therapies and identifying genetic components for swine resistance / susceptibility to PRRS . <S> <P>",
            "relation": "FINDINGS"
        }
    ]
}